    "narrative": "Today\u2019s lineup is anchored by three primary high-efficiency targets who benefit significantly from favorable matchups against weak rotations. **Cal Raleigh** (68.75) and **Brendan Donovan** (68.26) are our top plays, both capitalizing on a prime matchup against Buehler (5.19 xERA). **Donovan** gains an extra edge from his leadoff spot, while **Tyler Freeman** (68.67) mirrors this upside against Weiss (7.36 xERA), making our middle-infield and OF2 spots the engine of our offensive production today. Meanwhile, **Lawrence Butler** (68.12) is a strong start despite a poor BvP history; his massive +10% park factor and +13% platoon advantage against Leiter\u2019s 4.43 xERA make him a must-start despite the minor penalty for hitting seventh. \n\nWe are monitoring weather closely for **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** (67.08) and **Taylor Ward** (54.31), both of whom are facing a 36% rain risk. While **Ram\u00edrez** remains a lock due to his elite profile, **Ward** sits in a more precarious position near the middle of the pack. The most difficult bench decision involved **Jung Hoo Lee** (46.66), who was the first player cut from the active roster. While his platoon edge against Burns (2.76 xERA) is strong, the raw efficiency of **Matt Chapman** (48.03) and **Wenceel Perez** (50.77) marginally edged him out in our daily projections. Given our extreme emphasis on stolen base scarcity, we are keeping a close eye on **Wenceel Perez**, though he faces a slight efficiency dip due to the opposing pitcher\u2019s ability to hold runners. As a reminder, **Geraldo Perdomo** remains inactive due to a team off-day, and we continue to manage our overall game caps by benching **Drew Gilbert** (38.47) to stay beneath the 40.0 efficiency floor.",
